  "prompt": "How hard is it for a native English speaker to learn Vietnamese?",
  "response": "Learning Vietnamese can be challenging for native English speakers due to several factors:\n\n1. Tonal Language\n- Vietnamese is a tonal language with 6 different tones\n- Each tone can completely change the meaning of a word\n- This is very different from English, which is not tonal\n\n2. Grammar\n- Vietnamese grammar is significantly different from English\n- Verb tenses and sentence structures do not directly translate\n- Word order and grammatical particles can be complex\n\n3. Pronunciation\n- Some Vietnamese sounds do not exist in English\n- Pronunciation requires precise tone and sound production\n- Difficult consonant and vowel combinations\n\n4. Vocabulary\n- Very few cognates with English\n- Words often have no similarity to English equivalents\n- Large vocabulary to learn from scratch\n\n5. Writing System\n- Uses Latin alphabet with additional diacritical marks\n- Requires learning new pronunciation rules for marked letters\n\nDifficulty Rating:\n- US Foreign Service Institute categorizes Vietnamese as a \"Category III\" language\n- Estimated 1100 hours of study to reach professional working proficiency\n- Considered more difficult than Spanish or French, but less difficult than Arabic or Chinese\n\nOverall, Vietnamese is considered a difficult language for English speakers, requiring significant time and dedicated study.",
